You can nest arrays within other arrays. This is also called a multi-dimensional array.

Example:
const teams = [["Bulls", 23], ["White Sox", 45]];

Array indexes are used to access data inside arrays. They are written in the same bracket notation as strings, specifying an entry in the array. Arrays use zero-based indexing, so the first element has an index of 0.

Example:
const array = [50, 60, 70];
console.log(array[0]);
const data = array[1];

The console.log(array[0]) prints 50, and data has the value 60.

Unlike strings, the entries of arrays are mutable, meaning they can be changed freely, even if the array was declared with const.

Example:
const ourArray = [50, 40, 30];
ourArray[0] = 15;

After this, ourArray now has the value [15, 40, 30].

